  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States Approach\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Comprehensive federal legislation\n- Mandatory reporting requirements\n- Criminal and civil penalties\n- Focus on financial institution compliance\n\n2. European Union Approach\n- Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)\n- Harmonized legal framework across member states\n- Risk-based supervision\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Emphasis on transparency and information sharing\n\n3. United Kingdom Model\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Strict regulatory framework\n- Sophisticated financial intelligence unit\n- Extraterritorial enforcement capabilities\n- Strong international cooperation\n\n4. Swiss Approach\n- Historically more permissive banking secrecy laws\n- Recent reforms increasing transparency\n- Strict licensing and reporting requirements\n- International compliance pressures\n\n5. China's Regulatory Framework\n- Centralized enforcement\n- Stricter capital controls\n- Growing international cooperation\n- Increasing regulatory sophistication\n\n6. Common Regulatory Elements\n- Customer identification\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- International information exchange\n- Risk-based compliance mechanisms\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of these approaches?",
